<br>
The bar had once been glorious, that she could sense. She could hear the echoes of ghosts, the singing, the laughter, and she sensed something... ominous about. Was it this thing that led to the decay of the place? Whatever had happened? <br>
<br>
She ran a hand over the bar, dust rising up, making her eyes squint, and her nose tickle. She sneezed a moment, and again, and then again, then sniffed, taking out a white hanky and holding it to her face. "Phew, dust. And... sweat.. and... Tunare, what in Norrath is this about??" <br>
<br>
Xanta had smelled this smell before, when a body was too long gone. Only once had she worked the magic to bring back someone that far gone, but that had been different- that was love. She smiled at the thought of her fiance. He must be looking for her now, surely he was. And surely would he find her.<br>
<br>
Stepping behind the bar, she went through the bottles. A bit of rum, a bit of vodka, a few drops of wine, some brandy. She poured the last of some white wine into a goblet she'd pulled down from a rack, dusting it in her underskirts. <br>
<br>
Hopping up on the bar, thinking to bring some magic back, she began a slow song, a hum, almost, hoping, perhaps in vain, to bring back some of the folk. She was no bard, but she was a cleric, perhaps song could heal up this place, bring back a proper barmaid and tender, some old companions, old friends, and she sang, with the hope they'd follow the sound...<br>
<br>
<br>
<center><i>Through storms and long nights<br>
You were there,<br>
I followed you.<br>
Days I was lost without you,<br>
You followed through.<br>
I didn't mean to get so far, away.<br>
I thought you'd always be around,<br>
In your arms I thought I'd find home.<br>
<br>
There was no other place to be,<br>
No fire warmer than your heart<br>
I'd rather be.<br>
No adventure would keep me away,<br>
From you,<br>
As your love is the only journey<br>
I want to make.<br>
<br>
Around and around we go,<br>
Where we'd stop,<br>
Nobody knows,<br>
But may we always come back,<br>
To the place we were,<br>
Finding you, finding me.</center></i><br>
<br>
The song faded out, she hummed a bit, the melody catching in her head. She thought of the folks she had heard of coming here, and realized, ahhhh, it made sense, yes...<br>
<br>
<b>The Missed Note</b>...<br>
